{"source_key":"sha256-e05618dd9b62f1fced9a2b9f2f2081bc","record_index":15,"record_hash":"sha256:4c30a33759dfa6ebca6d63e3e03982834c5d70bab3598c0f7467ba02e56c7e21","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:22:38.675Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: cc60ca\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2819\nOutput:\n# Including Turns In Agentlog\n\nThis note explores an evolution of `but-agentlog`: add a durable concept of an\nagent session turn between the project-scoped session and the captured transcript\nrecords.\n\nThe motivation is the session-association problem. The older\n[Session Association Strategy](session-association-strategy.md) is right to be\ncautious about capture-time ownership, but it treats the captured session mostly\nas one coarse object. In practice, the hook flow already gives us a more useful\nunit: every stop hook invocation is effectively a capture after an agent turn.\n\nToday `but-agentlog` deduplicates transcript records into one project session:\n\n```text\nproject session -> transcript records\n```\n\nThat stores the conversation, but it loses which newly observed records belonged\nto which capture invocation. It also loses the repository state that was true at\nthat moment. A turn layer would preserve that missing context without forcing us\nto immediately claim that the session \"belongs\" to a branch, commit, change, or\npull request.\n\n## Product Use Cases\n\nKeep this grounded in the same two use cases as the rest of the agent-session\ncapture project.\n\n### 1. Session Handoff\n\nHandoff wants enough project-scoped session context to continue work on another\nmachine or with another agent. For this use case, turns help because they add\nstructure:\n\n- the session can be reconstructed as a sequence of user/agent interactions\n- a future reader can see the repository state around each interaction\n- consumers can choose the latest turn, a specific turn, or a window of turns\n  instead of treating the whole transcript as one flat blob\n\nHandoff does not necessarily need branch association. It mostly needs readable\nconversation records, ordering, and enough environment context to orient the\nnext agent.\n\n### 2. Review Sharing\n\nReview sharing wants a GitButler web view that can show reviewers what happened\nbehind a branc\n[TRUNCATED]\n commit\n\nAlso store a compact `observed_targets` summary on the turn detail. It should\ncontain the canonical branch, review, and change keys that were indexed for this\nturn. This keeps candidate verification and future index rebuilds cheap without\nduplicating the whole environment snapshot in every reader.\n\nPlain Git mode should use the same snapshot path as GitButler mode. The\nexpectation is that the GitButler workspace/head-info APIs expose a compatible\nstack/branch shape for plain Git repositories, so `but-agentlog` should not grow\na separate plain-Git fallback model unless the shared API proves insufficient.\n\nGitButler mode is more nuanced:\n\n- there may be multiple applied branches/stacks at the same time\n- there may be zero applied branches\n- stacked branches may mean both `bottom-refactor` and `top-feature` are\n  present, while the agent session is only relevant to `top-feature`\n- two applied branches such as `my-feature` and `other-stuff` may coexist even\n  when only one is relevant to the session\n\nDo not store a separate `checked_out_refs` field. It duplicates the stack/branch\nsnapshot and creates reader precedence questions. Also do not store graph\nprojection internals such as `is_entrypoint`; that is a traversal detail, not\ndurable product evidence for association.\n\nBranch names, relative file paths, review identifiers, change ids, commit ids,\nand commit file lists are acceptable for repo-scoped `gitbutler:*` metadata\nbecause they travel within the same repository metadata access boundary as the\ncode. Do not store absolute paths. Re-check this assumption before exposing the\nsame metadata in product surfaces with a narrower audience than repository\naccess, such as selected web review links.\n\nCanonical target keys should be defined before writing indexes:\n\n- branch key material: normalized full refname when available, with display name\n  kept separately for UI\n- review key material: provider plus repo-scoped review identity, for example\n  `github-pr:owner/repo#1284` when the owner/repo is available\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:22:38.675Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}